            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> For example:\r\n> \r\n> ```python\r\n> class Foo:\r\n>     def __init__(self, a: int) -> None: ...\r\n> ```\r\n> \r\n> would generate:\r\n> \r\n> ```cython\r\n> cdef class Foo:\r\n>     cpdef void __init__(self, int a)\r\n> ```\r\n\r\nBoth are not equivalent. Python methods are not `cpdef` methods, Python classes are not extension types, and Python `int` is not a C `int`. The mere fact that a `.pyi` file exists that contains Python declarations does not allow Cython to generate efficient C code.\r\n\r\nYou could probably [use Cython types](https://docs.cython.org/en/latest/src/tutorial/pure.html#pep-484-type-annotations) in your `.pyi` files, in which case it would be nice if Cython was able to pick them up. However, I'm not sure right now if decorators like `@cython.cclass` and `@cython.ccall` can be supported in `.pyi` files.\r\n\r\nThus, I'm not really convinced that this feature would be as helpful as you seem to think.",
